div.div: Now I want to deploy new version of code with zero downtime. Already Kubernetes has strategy in deployment to provide zero down time deployment with RollingUpdate strategy. So if you deploy the new image (with updated application version) directly using RollingUpdate strategy you wont get any downtime by using some options like maxUnavailable, minReadySeconds options but if there is any issue in the new version of code and because you already deployed it in the production, end users traffic gets routed to this new pods created out of new image, the end users faces the issues in accessing/using application before you realize and rollback to previous version end users already accessing the new application version and this is not recommended as end user experience issues and there will be a loss of business. So instead of going this way, we can go for Blue Green (Red/Black) Deployment. That means we bring a parallel environment(If two cluster Blue/Green Deployment) and deploy new image into our containers (Pods) and then using Internal Load Balance(ILB) QA team can access the application and test it for good amount of time and then after certifying that application is working fine, we can route the ender user traffic to the new nodes in the new cluster by updating target groups in ELB

div.div: In phase1: Now since I have Created pod in new deployment with same labels as that of pods in earlier deployment now the service routes the traffic to the new pod also. This pod has updated version of code. Now Whenever end users are trying to access the application some percent of the requests(few requests) reaches the new pod and end user gets response from new pod. Now lets say there is some issue with the new application code, and since only few requests are routing to this new pod with updated version of code all the users wont get effected, only few percentage of customers will get impacted. Now as their is a issue in the new code we can scale down this deployment pods to Zero, if we scale down pods to zero the requests wont go to that new pod (new change) by our service.
